Heidegger, M. (1954 / 1977 trans.). The question concerning technology. In The question concerning technology and other essays (W. Lovitt, Trans.). Harper. — The shorter, more accessible Heidegger entry point.
Han, B.-C. (2010 / 2015 trans.). The burnout society (E. Butler, Trans.). Stanford University Press. — Korean-German philosopher writing directly about how constant performance and connection erode selfhood.
Han, B.-C. (2019 / 2020 trans.). The disappearance of rituals (D. Steuer, Trans.). Polity. — Han’s later treatment of ritual closure as cognitive technology — directly relevant to the chapter’s “rituals of conversational closure” guideline.
For the contemplative traditions specifically:

Merton, T. (1949). Seeds of contemplation. New Directions. — Christian contemplative tradition from a 20th-century Trappist who wrote about silence in modern terms.
Hanh, T. N. (1975). The miracle of mindfulness. Beacon. — Buddhist framing of present-moment attention, accessible to non-Buddhist readers.
Goldstein, J., & Kornfield, J. (1987). Seeking the heart of wisdom: The path of insight meditation. Shambhala. — The clearest Western introduction to Vipassana and Noble Silence.
Foster, R. J. (1978). Celebration of discipline. HarperOne. — Cross-traditional Christian treatment of solitude, silence, and other contemplative practices as disciplines rather than experiences.
